Ye  I was in NUS Chem  FoS which is part of the current CHS

Back in my time  we had compulsory modules that would expose us to general  physical  organic  inorganic and analytical chemistry + lab techniques in first two yearsFrom third year onward there were compulsory lab modules but we could choose other modules that fit our personal interests. That was when I stopped doing org chem altogether and focused on physical and analytical chem. I think I did a module of Inorg chem and disliked it too hahahaThen fourth year we spent most of our time completing a FYP and doing a few random modules. My project was on chemical synthesis of nano particles (specifically  quantum dots)
These days  there are more specialisations offered to Chem majors  so my experience is outdated already

Honestly hor  I spent most of my first 2.5 years or so being very involved in student activities related side hustle. Coz I thought my work would require me to not just be good in content knowledge. I was more academically disciplined only mid third year onwards

I was particularly weak in the area of retrosynthesis and it did not help that I did not sit my ass down to study having spent most of my time doing non-academic work instead. I could still cope with the other modules but my org chem suffered from the lack of effort :p
do you think if you went back in time will you be more studious in y1 and y2

No way. I would have studied less hahaha. I was not as talented as some of my batch mates. Between putting in a whole lot of effort to get FCH vs getting a 2nd Upp comfortably + having time to gain exposure in non-acad areas  I definitely choose the latter
U believe the latter still benefitted u more?

Yep. In Year 1  I was a project director and in year 2  I was the VP in my facultyâ€™s equivalent of SCI learnt invaluable lessons organising events  working with various stakeholders  and spent many precious moments being with friends whom I still keep in contact with
